Comment:
This is probably one of my favorite Disney movie. 

My own complaints would be that no character had facial tattoos. I think that would have added a lot more. It would have been interesting if Maui had facial tattoos. But I guess the creators decided that it would be distracting or it would kind of "block out" his facial expressions, I guess... Or maybe just a moko kauae (chin tattoo) for some women, maybe Moana's mom or grandma, or maybe only a background character. I think that would have added a real charm and beauty to them. 
My other complaint is that the Haka was kind of rushed. I would have liked seeing more of that in the movie.

But either way it's an amazing movie!

Title: Moana Official Trailer
Comment:
I just watched it in theaters. 
Now we're gonna talk about it.
In detail.

*SPOILERS*







I.....freaking......adored this movie. It was really good and definitely worth watching. The story is about the island of Tahiti, the mother of all islands, when it is healthy, all other islands are healthy. Maui (a demigod) steals the heart of Tahiti to posses the power of nature. When he tries to flee the island, he gets pulled under by a lava monster thus causing him to lose the heart of Tahiti and his Hook (a weapon that allows him to shapeshift) 

Later, we see that another island that is dying because of Tahiti's missing heart, for Tahiti's well being affects the well being of other islands, so it is up to Moana to restore balance to the islands of the ocean. Along the way she finds Maui who is forced to help Moana replace the heart of the island. As their journey progresses, they must fight the monsters of the ocean and try to get along with each other in order to solve this quest. 

Now while Frozen is currently my favorite animated film of all time, this movie had the same formula as Frozen and it works friggin perfectly. Moana (like Anna) is awkward, clumsy and relateable. They both share the same mission: To journey out of their homes and fulfill a prophecy that will restore balance and make everything normal again. Moana's sidekick (Maui) is much like Anna's sidekick (Kristoff). He is confident and sure of himself, but does have a weak spot. 

So Moana goes to the island of Tahiti and ends up finding out that there is no island. The island of Tahiti has been so contaminated that it is no longer and island. It turns out to be the lava monster that causes Moana and Maui so much distress. It's the lava monster guarding Tahiti's island, that IS the island. Moana manages to put the heart back and the island is cleansed and purified of dirt and evil. Just like Anna must find her sister and try to get her to lift the spell of Arandelle, Moana's objective is very similar. 

I would rate it 10/10. The songs are catchy, the characters are conplex and 3 dimensional, the animation is FLAWLESS, the story is fantastic and the ambiance is magnificent. Just like the masterpiece that is Frozen, Moana accomplished the very same.

Best Disney movies of 2010's:
Tangeled
Frozen
Big Hero 6
Moana

Title: Moana Official Trailer
Comment:
I like how Moana is very similar to other Disney movies, but also very unique in many ways:

Ariel wants to go to land, not only because she is interested in the humans, but also because of love. She feels held back by her father.
Moana wants to sail to the sea because it calls out to her, and because she wants to help her people and she feels it is who she is. She also feels held back by her father.

Mulan feels like she is not the perfect daughter and does not meet the expectations of her parents, and is struggling to find who she is.
Moana also feels like she is not the perfect daughter and does not meet the expectations of her father, and feels like the ocean is who she is.

Rapunzel and Flynn reluctantly get along, but confide in each other and eventually fall in love.
Moana and Maui reluctantly get along, but confide in each other and share a deep bond of friendship- even if it isn't love.

Belle is the odd one out because the rest of her village is fine with having a plain life without adventure, and they think she is crazy for reading. She wants to be out in the world on an adventure.
Moana is the odd one out because the rest of her village is fine with staying on the island,  but she wants to be out in the sea, like a voyager.

Merida is brave and independent, and does not want love or to be a perfect princess- she is very rebellious.
Moana is brave and independent, and barely thinks about love- she is somewhat less rebellious, and does not want to let down her family and people, but still wants to be with the sea.

When will Disney drop the "princess" shtick and start making movies about regular people? Why can't they be just regular girls\women? 
Also, am I the only one that feels all the Disney-Pixar age character designs for the main female characters are all basically the same with minor changes? I think it's much worse than the 2D Disney age..(and I'm not even talking about them always looking like models with a perfect everything, though that goes for every Disney movie ever).
This character is a big improvement and actually looks different, but it feels like they used the same basic template again and then just changed it a bit to fit her ethnicity. 
Disney will probably always be successful, because they're DISNEY. But in terms of content, there are other animation companies (aside from anime related, since that is in a completely different category to me), like Dreamworks for example(only some of their movies though), I enjoy much more nowadays.. a lot more there in terms of diversity, plot, characters, atmosphere.. I just really hope this movie won't be as disappointing as the previous Disney-Pixar ones.

The first Polynesians migrated out from Samoa over 3000 years ago. They populated all the islands, the last islands to be populated were Hawaii and nz/aotearoa. In a fully Global world where countries are struggling economically especially in the European Union.  It is great to see a few small island showing that it is possible to sustain and even flourish in this environment.  Samoa, Tonga and Fiji are shining examples of how small islands can be fully independent be Majority Polynesian and maintain and celebrate their uniqueness in Western dominated world, Cheee Hoooo.

Comment: I see their are comments suggesting there is no love interest due to feminism ideals. However this has nothing to do with feminism. Moana is a film based on traditional Polynesian cultures of the South Pacific, where it is strictly forbidden for teenage girls of Moana's age to associate with the opposite sex in a romantic way. This cultural custom applies right until they come of age.
